         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot. Garden ¶ 23./6/64 ¶ Dear Mr Bentham. ¶  ¶ I am glad, that you caused already some 2 more boxes with Leguminosae more to be returned pr Sussex, for which I shall look out[.] For your pro...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">64.06.23</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 147.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot. Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">23./6/64</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Mr Bentham.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am glad, that you caused already some 2 more boxes with <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name> more to be returned pr Sussex, for which I shall look out[.] For your proofsheets I am eagerly looking forward, as I do not like to resume my labors on the plants of Victoria, until I know your views. I should not have thought that we had 250 phyllodineous <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>e, but I may not be acquainted with all the S.W. &amp; N.W. species.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Would it not be well to identify on this occasion the <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name> of Dampier, figured in the work on his travels?<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M is presumably referring to Dampier (1729), to which he had access (see M to W. Hooker, 24 May 1862 (in this edition as 62-05-24a)). <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>However, none of the species illustrated on the three plates of plants from New Holland (i.e. Australia) in this work have been identified as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
                     </seg> species; see George (1999). Bentham does not cite Dampier in his collection notes for these of for any other species of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
                     </seg> in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2, pp. 301-421.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As regards <name key="Glycyrrhiza">Glycyrrhiza</name> I was evidently led astray by R Brown, for when before his appendix to Sturts travels appeared in 1848<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Brown (1849).</p>
               </note> I saw it for the first time on the Murray lagoons, I was struck with the resemblance of the plant to <name key="Glycyrrhiza%20echinata">Glycyrrhiza echinata</name>, but not having my <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">University</hi>
               </seg> herbarium then with me, which arrived only some years later from Europe I could not compare the plants. To me as an Examiner in Therapeutics &amp; Materia medica on our University, it is certainly not creditable, that I should have not recognized a true glycyrrhiza.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The roots of various species of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Glycyrrhiza">Glycyrrhiza</name>
                     </seg>, especially <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. glabra</seg>, yield liquorice, used as a purge.</p>
               </note> From the enclosed memorandum you will perceive, that the Embryo of <name key="Hymenanthera">Hymenanthera</name> is not correctly described in your genera plantarum,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> where you seemed to have adopted implicitly the character from Fitch's plate.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker (1853-5), vol. 1, t. 7, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Hymenanthera">Hymenanthera</name> crassifolia</seg>; 'Fitch del &amp; Lith.' The memorandum referred to has not been located.</p>
               </note> I have also some error to point out in regard to <name key="Brucea%20Sumatrana">Brucea Sumatrana</name>. The petals of this &amp; seemingly also of B. antidysenterica are not narrow &amp;c.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>RBr. <name key="Pentadynamis">Pentadynamis</name> is nothing else but Crotalaria dried in a young fructifying state, when the legumen may appear to be flat. I should never have imagined that <name key="Zornia%20chaetophora">Zornia chaetophora</name> could be reduced to any other species, from what I saw of it on the northern sandstone table land. Have you intermediate forms from other countries?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Some of the notes in the now transmitted two fascicles of the fragmenta may interest you.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With kindest regards</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">Ferd Mueller</seg>
            </p>
